<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1906-09-13T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1906-09-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="201" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d201">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Ambassador <persName type="from">Thompson</persName>
                                to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1906-09-13"><hi rend="italic">September 13,
                                    1906</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Yours 12th relative to American schooner <hi rend="italic">Hatteras</hi>,
                            second paragraph, article 5, of Mexican law, issued December 18, 1902,
                            provides a maritime belt of 20 kilometers in which vessels of all
                            nationalities can be inspected by Mexican men-of-war or coast patrol
                            vessels. If the department thinks this law should be questioned, will
                            you kindly give further instructions.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">D. E. Thompson.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>